Gentrification index measure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is no general accepted definition of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gentrification
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

. The term was coined by British sociologist Ruth Glass in 1964. She was describing the displacement of lower-class worker residents in urban neighborhoods by middle-class people in Islington, London
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "gentrification_def"

\end_inset

. This vague and abstract definition makes it even harder to measure the extent of gentrification of a whole city quantitatively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea behind getting a number for the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

amount
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of gentrification happening in a city is to merely focus on the change of the household income with respect to time. All other census data, which claim to measure gentrification, can be viewed as its effects according to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "gentr_causes"

\end_inset

. Hence, we decided to divide a city into districts by virtue of the town subdivision (???), and compared the median household income per month (MHI) of each district from data 10 years apart. To assure that the increase is free from inflation and other economic growth factors we calculate the increase of MHI in each district 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=x(i=District)$
\end_inset

 relative to the increase of the mean MHI of the whole city 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}$
\end_inset

. More precisely, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
x_{i}=\frac{\mathrm{MHI}(i,2016)-\mathrm{MHI}(i,2007)}{\mathrm{MHI}(i,2016)},\quad\tilde{x}=\frac{\widehat{\mathrm{MHI}}(2016)-\widehat{\mathrm{MHI}}(2007)}{\widehat{\mathrm{MHI}}(2016)},\label{eq:mhi}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ \widehat{}\ $
\end_inset

 denotes the average of MHI in a particular year over all districts 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

. Then we use 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}$
\end_inset

 as a reference for the increase 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

. Tab.
\begin_inset Formula $\,$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Median-household-income"

\end_inset

 shows this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

relative
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 increase of the MHI, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}=\left(x_{i}-\tilde{x}\right)/\tilde{x}$
\end_inset

, in case of Berlin. Furthermore, we are also interested in the change of the number of household 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i}=\mathrm{N}(i,2016)/\mathrm{N}(i,2007)$
\end_inset

 in a certain district. This also influences gentrification. If, for instance, rental fees increase but the number of household decrease in a certain area, then we can assume that several cheaper households were displaced by a few expensive ones.
