\begin_layout Standard
The final step consists of putting the quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 together in a way which results in a meaningful measure of gentrification. We propose that the following formula is a comprehensive quantity to measure the gentrification of a city, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
G=\sum_{i=1}^{N}\frac{G_{i}}{H_{i}},\quad G_{i}=\sum_{j=1,\,j\neq i}^{N}\frac{\left|r_{i}-r_{j}\right|^{2}}{\left\langle i,j\right\rangle ^{2}}.\label{eq:gindex}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

We call 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

 the gentrification index of a city and the gentrification index of the city district 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 respectively. Due to the fact that gentrification is a rather subjective notion, and the fact that in the perspective of citizens it manifests itself the most when adjacent neighborhoods are compared, we take the square of our distance measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle $
\end_inset

. This has the effect to soften the differences between two districts when they are far apart. The meaning of the numerator in Eq.
\begin_inset Formula $\,$
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gindex"

\end_inset

) is clear when we write out the squares, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{i}^{2}-x_{j}^{2}\right)/\tilde{x}^{2}.$
\end_inset

 The numerator is smaller, if the mean MHI of the city 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}$
\end_inset

 is high. Then, two district with a big difference in the MHI 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}-x_{j}$
\end_inset

 are going to make 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

 small, whereas on those where the difference is small 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}$
\end_inset

 has no effect at all. With this feature we can take into account the overall increase of the MHI in a city. The gentrification index of an city with a low 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}$
\end_inset

 but a distinctive shift of citizens of different working-classes shall be especially big, as we can then assume that wealthier people haven't moved in from beyond the city at an above average rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although, the above argumentation is sensible, we can't be sure if (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
